<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<html xmlns:MadCap="http://www.madcapsoftware.com/Schemas/MadCap.xsd" MadCap:conditions="Products.Capture,Products.Mimic" MadCap:lastBlockDepth="2" MadCap:lastHeight="149" MadCap:lastWidth="505">
    <body>
        <p>You can create a shading effect in conjunction with a shape that you add to<MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="Products.Capture"> an image</MadCap:conditionalText><MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="Products.Mimic"> a frame</MadCap:conditionalText>. This is a useful effect, for example, if you want to highlight a particular area of<MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="Products.Capture"> an image</MadCap:conditionalText><MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="Products.Mimic"> a frame</MadCap:conditionalText>, without hiding the rest of the<MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="Products.Capture"> image</MadCap:conditionalText><MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="Products.Mimic"> frame</MadCap:conditionalText>. You can draw a shape around the area of the<MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="Products.Capture"> image</MadCap:conditionalText><MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="Products.Mimic"> frame</MadCap:conditionalText> that you want to emphasize and then apply the shading effect, determining the amount of darkness or lightness of the shading. The area inside the shape remains clear, but the rest of the<MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="Products.Capture"> image</MadCap:conditionalText><MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="Products.Mimic"> frame</MadCap:conditionalText> around the shape becomes shaded. You can even have multiple shapes on<MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="Products.Capture"> an image</MadCap:conditionalText><MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="Products.Mimic"> a frame</MadCap:conditionalText>, each with a shading effect.</p>
    </body>
</html>